hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a simplified one-dimensional model for an electron that is confined within a linear defect in a crystal lattice. The quantum state of this electron is described by a time-independent wave function, $\Psi(x)$. The wave function is non-zero only within a small region of length $2a$, centered at the origin. Specifically, the wave function is given by:

$$
\Psi(x) =
\begin{cases}
C & \text{for } -a \le x \le a \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$

Here, $a$ is a positive real constant representing half the length of the confinement region, and $C$ is a normalization constant. In quantum mechanics, the probability of finding the particle somewhere in all of space must be equal to 1. Determine the value of the positive, real normalization constant $C$ in terms of the parameter $a$.
